    <!-- Blog Post Pages -->
    <div class="page-content" id="blog-post-page">
        <!-- Individual blog post pages would be loaded here dynamically -->
        <!-- For example, when clicking "Read More" on Raigad Fort -->
        <div class="blog-post-header" id="raigad-post" style="background-image: url('https://i.ibb.co/3yYmJKGC/istockphoto-1226700711-612x612.jpg');">
            <div class="blog-post-title">
                <h1>Raigad Fort: The Fortress of Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj</h1>
                <div class="blog-post-meta">
                    <span><i class="far fa-user"></i> By Rahul Sharma</span>
                    <span><i class="far fa-calendar"></i> April 5, 2025</span>
                    <span><i class="far fa-clock"></i> 10 min read</span>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="blog-post-content">
            <div class="container">
                <p>Perched high in the Sahyadri mountain range of Maharashtra, Raigad Fort stands as a testament to Maratha valor and architectural brilliance. Once the capital of Chhatrapati Shivaji's kingdom, this hill fort offers not just breathtaking views but a deep dive into a pivotal chapter of Indian history.</p>

                <h2>Historical Significance</h2>
                <p>Originally called Rairi, the fort was seized by Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj in 1656 from the royal house of the Chandrarrao Mores. Recognizing its strategic importance, Shivaji rebuilt and strengthened the fort, making it his capital in 1674 when he was crowned as the official king of the Maratha Empire.</p>

                <img src="https://i.ibb.co/3yYmJKGC/istockphoto-1226700711-612x612.jpg">
                <p>The fort witnessed many significant events, including Shivaji's coronation and the establishment of the Maratha navy. It remained the capital until the fall of the Maratha Empire to the British in 1818.</p>

                <h2>Architectural Marvel</h2>
                <p>Raigad's architecture showcases the military genius of the Marathas. The fort sits at an elevation of 820 meters (2,700 ft) above sea level, with its main entrance, the Maha Darwaja, positioned such that enemy elephants would find it impossible to charge.</p>

                <p>Key structures within the fort include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Raj Bhavan:</strong> Shivaji's residence</li>
                    <li><strong>Raj Sabha:</strong> The durbar hall where official ceremonies were held</li>
                    <li><strong>Holi Cha Mal:</strong> The queen's quarters</li>
                    <li><strong>Takmak Tok:</strong> A cliff from which prisoners were thrown as punishment</li>
                    <li><strong>Ganga Sagar Lake:</strong> The main water reservoir</li>
                </ul>

                <img src="https://i.ibb.co/3yYmJKGC/istockphoto-1226700711-612x612.jpg">
                <h2>Visiting Raigad Today</h2>
                <p>Modern visitors to Raigad can reach the fort via a 1,737-step climb or a ropeway that offers spectacular aerial views. The Maharashtra government has developed the site with museums, information centers, and amenities while preserving its historical integrity.</p>

                <p>The best time to visit is between October and March when the weather is pleasant. The light and sound show in the evening brings the fort's history to life through dramatic narration and lighting effects.</p>

                <blockquote>
                    "Raigad is not just stone and mortar - it's the embodiment of Maratha pride and self-rule. Walking through its gates is like stepping back into Shivaji's era." - Local Historian
                </blockquote>

                <h2>Personal Experience</h2>
                <p>When I visited Raigad last monsoon, the mist-covered fort had an almost mystical quality. Standing in the Raj Sabha, I could almost hear the echoes of past discussions that shaped Maratha history. The view from the top is unparalleled - on clear days, you can see for miles across the Western Ghats.</p>

                <p>The most moving moment was seeing Shivaji's samadhi (memorial) near the fort. Despite its simple appearance, the site commands deep respect from all visitors.</p>

                <h2>Travel Tips</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>Wear comfortable shoes as there's considerable walking involved</li>
                    <li>Carry water and snacks, though basic facilities are available</li>
                    <li>Hire a guide to fully appreciate the historical significance</li>
                    <li>Visit early to avoid crowds and afternoon heat</li>
                    <li>Don't miss the sunset views from the western bastions</li>
                </ul>

                <p>Raigad Fort remains one of Maharashtra's most important historical sites and a must-visit for anyone interested in India's rich past. More than just a tourist attraction, it's a symbol of resistance, good governance, and visionary leadership that continues to inspire.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    <!-- [Previous header, nav, and other sections remain exactly the same until the blog post pages] -->

    <!-- Blog Post Pages -->
    <div class="page-content" id="blog-post-page">
        <!-- Individual blog post pages would be loaded here dynamically -->
        <!-- For example, when clicking "Read More" on Eiffel Tower -->
        <div class="blog-post-header" id="eiffel-post" style="background-image: url('https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1528909514045-2fa4ac7a08ba?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1470&q=80');">
            <div class="blog-post-title">
                <h1>Eiffel Tower: The Iron Lady of Paris</h1>
                <div class="blog-post-meta">
                    <span><i class="far fa-user"></i> By Rahul Sharma</span>
                    <span><i class="far fa-calendar"></i> April 11, 2025</span>
                    <span><i class="far fa-clock"></i> 9 min read</span>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        
        <div class="blog-post-content>     
            <div class="container">
                <p>The <strong>Eiffel Tower</strong>, or <em>La Tour Eiffel</em> in French, stands as the most iconic symbol of Paris and one of the most recognized landmarks in the world. Located on the Champ de Mars near the Seine River, this towering iron structure draws millions of visitors every year.</p>

                <h2>Historical Significance</h2>
                <p>The Eiffel Tower was constructed between 1887 and 1889 as the entrance arch to the 1889 Exposition Universelle (World's Fair), held to celebrate the 100th anniversary of the French Revolution. Designed by engineer Gustave Eiffel, the tower was initially met with criticism but has since become a beloved emblem of French art, culture, and ingenuity.</p>
                
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1528909514045-2fa4ac7a08ba?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1470&q=80">
                
                <p>Standing 330 meters (1,083 feet) tall, the tower was the tallest man-made structure in the world until the completion of the Chrysler Building in New York in 1930.</p>

                <h2>Architectural Marvel</h2>
                <p>The Eiffel Tower was built using over 18,000 individual iron parts and 2.5 million rivets. Its open-lattice design not only gives it aesthetic charm but also provides immense structural strength. The tower has three levels accessible to the public, offering panoramic views of Paris from every angle.</p>
                
                <p>Key highlights include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>The First Floor:</strong> Features a glass floor, restaurants, and exhibits</li>
                    <li><strong>The Second Floor:</strong> Home to the famous "Le Jules Verne" restaurant</li>
                    <li><strong>The Summit:</strong> Offers breathtaking 360-degree views of the city</li>
                </ul>
                
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1529516542053-1f831f86c45f?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1470&q=80">

                <h2>Visiting the Eiffel Tower Today</h2>
                <p>Whether by stairs or elevator, ascending the Eiffel Tower is a must-do for any traveler in Paris. The tower is beautifully lit each night, and every hour after sunset, it sparkles for five magical minutes. Seasonal events and exhibitions are frequently held within its structure.</p>
                
                <p>The tower is open year-round, though spring and autumn offer the best weather and lighter crowds. Booking tickets online in advance is highly recommended to skip long lines.</p>
                
                <blockquote>
                    "The Eiffel Tower isn't just a landmark --- it's a love letter in iron, written to the skies of Paris." - Local Parisian Guide
                </blockquote>

                <h2>Personal Experience</h2>
                <p>During my visit to the Eiffel Tower, I was stunned by the architectural elegance and the views from the top. Watching the sun set over the Seine while the city lights began to glow was an unforgettable experience. The sparkling tower at night felt straight out of a dream.</p>
                
                <p>Enjoying a croissant beneath the tower, surrounded by artists and the sound of street music, truly captured the soul of Paris for me.</p>

                <h2>Travel Tips</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>Buy your tickets online to avoid queues</li>
                    <li>Visit early morning or late evening for fewer crowds</li>
                    <li>Carry a camera --- the views are spectacular</li>
                    <li>Bring a jacket if visiting the summit --- it's windy!</li>
                    <li>Stay after sunset to see the hourly sparkle</li>
                </ul>
                
                <p>The Eiffel Tower continues to inspire awe and romance more than a century after its construction. Whether you admire it from afar or climb to the top, this Parisian jewel is a must-see for every traveler exploring the world.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Back button for blog posts -->
        <div class="container" style="margin-bottom: 50px;">
            <a href="#" class="btn" id="back-to-blog"><i class="fas fa-arrow-left"></i> Back to Blog</a>
        </div>

        <!-- Burj Khalifa Post -->
        <div class="blog-post-header" id="burj-post" style="background-image: url('https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1604066867775-43f48b4b2b22?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1470&q=80');">
            <div class="blog-post-title">
                <h1>Burj Khalifa: The Tallest Marvel of Modern Architecture</h1>
                <div class="blog-post-meta">
                    <span><i class="far fa-user"></i> By Rahul Sharma</span>
                    <span><i class="far fa-calendar"></i> April 11, 2025</span>
                    <span><i class="far fa-clock"></i> 8 min read</span>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="blog-post-content">
            <div class="container">
                <p>Standing tall amidst the futuristic skyline of Dubai, the <strong>Burj Khalifa</strong> is not only the world's tallest building but a global icon of innovation and architectural excellence. Soaring at 828 meters (2,717 feet), it dominates the city and offers awe-inspiring views, luxury, and engineering brilliance.</p>

                <h2>Historical Significance</h2>
                <p>Inaugurated on January 4, 2010, the Burj Khalifa was built as part of Dubai's vision to transform into a global hub. Originally named "Burj Dubai," the tower was renamed in honor of Sheikh Khalifa bin Zayed Al Nahyan, the President of the UAE. It symbolizes the ambition and rapid development of the UAE in the 21st century.</p>
                
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1604066867775-43f48b4b2b22?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1470&q=80">
                
                <p>The skyscraper is part of the larger Downtown Dubai development and plays a central role in the city's tourism and business sectors.</p>

                <h2>Architectural Marvel</h2>
                <p>Designed by architect Adrian Smith of Skidmore, Owings & Merrill, the Burj Khalifa combines Islamic architecture with cutting-edge design. Its triple-lobed footprint is inspired by the Hymenocallis flower. The structure is primarily reinforced concrete, with a spire composed of structural steel.</p>
                
                <p>Key features include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Observation Decks:</strong> "At the Top" on the 124th and 125th floors, and "At the Top SKY" on the 148th floor</li>
                    <li><strong>Armani Hotel:</strong> Luxury accommodations designed by Giorgio Armani</li>
                    <li><strong>Residential Units:</strong> Premium apartments with stunning views of Dubai</li>
                    <li><strong>The Dubai Fountain:</strong> A choreographed fountain show set on the Burj Lake</li>
                </ul>
                
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1611309454929-53d663cfb4c0?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1470&q=80">

                <h2>Visiting Burj Khalifa Today</h2>
                <p>Visitors can experience the thrill of high-speed elevators that take you to the observation decks, offering unparalleled views of Dubai's skyline, desert, and coastline. The tower sparkles at night with LED light shows and often hosts grand New Year's Eve fireworks displays.</p>
                
                <p>Tickets can be booked online, and it's best to visit around sunset for a breathtaking transition from day to night.</p>
                
                <blockquote>
                    "The Burj Khalifa isn't just tall --- it's a beacon of human ambition, pushing the boundaries of what's possible." - Dubai City Guide
                </blockquote>

                <h2>Personal Experience</h2>
                <p>My visit to the Burj Khalifa was nothing short of surreal. From the 148th floor, the city looked like a futuristic model --- a mesmerizing mix of desert and skyscrapers. The interactive displays inside also offer insight into the tower's construction and Dubai's transformation.</p>
                
                <p>Watching the Dubai Fountain from above while sipping coffee at the observation lounge was the highlight of the experience.</p>

                <h2>Travel Tips</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>Book your tickets in advance, especially for sunset hours</li>
                    <li>Visit the Dubai Mall next door --- it's one of the world's largest</li>
                    <li>Arrive early to explore the exhibits and enjoy the views longer</li>
                    <li>Don't forget your camera --- the view is Instagram-worthy!</li>
                    <li>Check if a light or fountain show is scheduled during your visit</li>
                </ul>
                
                <p>The Burj Khalifa stands not only as an architectural feat but as a symbol of vision, determination, and global unity. It's a must-see for any world traveler.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Back button for blog posts -->
