        <div class="blog-post-content">
            <div class="container">
                <p>Rising gracefully from the Honshu plains, <strong>Mount Fuji</strong> is Japan's tallest peak and most iconic symbol. This majestic, snow-capped stratovolcano is not only a geological wonder but also a sacred site revered in Japanese culture and art.</p>

                <h2>Historical Significance</h2>
                <p>Mount Fuji, or "Fujisan" in Japanese, has been worshipped for centuries. It's considered one of Japan's "Three Holy Mountains" alongside Mount Tate and Mount Haku. Pilgrimages to the summit began in the 7th century, and the volcano has inspired countless haikus, artworks, and spiritual traditions over time.</p>
                
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1601108995695-42c25f5bb227?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1470&q=80">
                
                <p>The mountain last erupted in 1707, and although dormant since then, it remains a powerful presence in Japanese consciousness and identity.</p>

                <h2>Natural Marvel</h2>
                <p>Standing at 3,776 meters (12,389 feet), Mount Fuji is visible from Tokyo on clear days. The symmetrical cone, often capped in snow, is a breathtaking sight that draws hikers, climbers, and photographers from around the globe.</p>
                
                <p>Key highlights around Mount Fuji include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Fuji Five Lakes:</strong> Scenic lakes at the base offering reflections of the mountain</li>
                    <li><strong>Chureito Pagoda:</strong> A famous spot for iconic views of Fuji framed with cherry blossoms</li>
                    <li><strong>Fujisan Sengen Shrine:</strong> Starting point for ancient pilgrimages</li>
                    <li><strong>Yoshida Trail:</strong> The most popular route to the summit</li>
                    <li><strong>Lake Kawaguchi:</strong> A serene area for nature lovers and Fuji-view seekers</li>
                </ul>
                
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1580297101715-07c3d823c9c0?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1470&q=80">

                <h2>Visiting Mount Fuji Today</h2>
                <p>Mount Fuji is open for climbing during the official season from early July to early September. Climbers can begin their ascent at various stations, with most aiming to witness the sunrise --- a phenomenon called "Goraiko."</p>
                
                <p>Outside of climbing season, tourists can enjoy views from hot springs, explore nature trails, and visit heritage sites nearby. Public transport and tours from Tokyo make the journey very accessible.</p>
                
                <blockquote>
                    "Mount Fuji is more than just a mountain --- it's a spiritual experience. Every view of it feels like witnessing a national treasure." -- Tokyo Travel Guide
                </blockquote>

                <h2>Personal Experience</h2>
                <p>My trip to Mount Fuji during autumn was unforgettable. The vibrant fall foliage around the lakes created a stunning contrast against Fuji's white peak. I didn't climb to the summit, but a peaceful walk around Lake Kawaguchi made me feel deeply connected to nature.</p>
                
                <p>Standing at the Chureito Pagoda during sunset, with the mountain glowing behind it, was the kind of moment you never forget.</p>

                <h2>Travel Tips</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>Check the weather forecast before planning your visit</li>
                    <li>Climbing is best done with proper gear and preparation</li>
                    <li>Go early to avoid crowds, especially in cherry blossom or autumn seasons</li>
                    <li>Stay overnight in a ryokan (traditional inn) for a full cultural experience</li>
                    <li>Visit an onsen (hot spring) with a view of Fuji for the ultimate relaxation</li>
                </ul>
                
                <p>Mount Fuji remains a beacon of peace, beauty, and endurance --- a must-visit destination for travelers seeking both natural wonder and cultural depth.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Back button for blog posts -->
        <div class="container" style="margin-bottom: 50px;">
            <a href="#" class="btn" id="back-to-blog"><i class="fas fa-arrow-left"></i> Back to Blog</a>
        </div>

        <!-- Blue Lagoon Post -->
        <div class="blog-post-header" id="blue-lagoon-post" style="background-image: url('https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1551887373-6f5a5fb85b04?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1470&q=80');">
            <div class="blog-post-title">
                <h1>The Blue Lagoon: Iceland's Geothermal Wonder</h1>
                <div class="blog-post-meta">
                    <span><i class="far fa-user"></i> By Rahul Sharma</span>
                    <span><i class="far fa-calendar"></i> April 11, 2025</span>
                    <span><i class="far fa-clock"></i> 7 min read</span>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="blog-post-content">
            <div class="container">
                <p>Nestled in a lava field near Grindavík, the <strong>Blue Lagoon</strong> is one of Iceland's most iconic destinations. With its surreal milky-blue waters and steamy atmosphere, this geothermal spa is both a modern retreat and a natural marvel, offering relaxation and rejuvenation in the heart of volcanic landscapes.</p>

                <h2>Natural Origins & Significance</h2>
                <p>Formed in 1976 by runoff from a nearby geothermal power plant, the Blue Lagoon was initially an accidental creation. However, people soon discovered the water's unique combination of minerals, especially silica and sulfur, had healing properties --- particularly beneficial for skin conditions like psoriasis.</p>
                
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1551887373-6f5a5fb85b04?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1470&q=80">
                
                <p>Today, the lagoon is an internationally renowned spa and a symbol of Iceland's blend of nature and innovation.</p>

                <h2>Relaxation and Facilities</h2>
                <p>The Blue Lagoon maintains a temperature of about 37--40°C (98--104°F) year-round, making it an inviting escape in any season. Guests can indulge in:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Silica Mud Masks:</strong> Natural masks provided in-water for skin care</li>
                    <li><strong>Swim-up Bar:</strong> Enjoy smoothies or prosecco while soaking</li>
                    <li><strong>Lava Restaurant:</strong> Fine dining with panoramic views of the lava fields</li>
                    <li><strong>Retreat Spa:</strong> Luxurious treatment areas and private lagoons</li>
                    <li><strong>Saunas & Steam Rooms:</strong> Built into lava rocks for added ambiance</li>
                </ul>
                
                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1572276596237-5fa36c0db646?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1470&q=80">

                <h2>Visiting the Blue Lagoon</h2>
                <p>Located about 45 minutes from Reykjavík and just 20 minutes from Keflavík International Airport, the Blue Lagoon is easily accessible for travelers. It's often the first or last stop on an Iceland itinerary.</p>
                
                <p>Advance booking is essential, especially during peak seasons. Entry includes a towel, silica mask, and access to showers and locker rooms. Premium options offer robes, slippers, and drinks.</p>
                
                <blockquote>
                    "The Blue Lagoon isn't just a spa --- it's a sanctuary where earth's raw elements soothe your soul." -- Icelandic Tourism Board
                </blockquote>

                <h2>Personal Experience</h2>
                <p>When I stepped into the mist-covered lagoon, the warm water melted away the fatigue of travel. Floating with a silica mask on my face, I could feel the stress of city life dissolve. The contrast of icy air and steamy waters was invigorating.</p>
                
                <p>As the sun set behind the lava fields, the entire pool glowed in hues of blue and orange --- a sight I'll never forget.</p>

                <h2>Travel Tips</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>Book tickets online in advance --- slots sell out quickly</li>
                    <li>Bring a waterproof phone case for photos in the water</li>
                    <li>Condition your hair well --- the minerals can make it stiff</li>
                    <li>Try visiting in the evening for fewer crowds and magical lighting</li>
                    <li>Combine your visit with nearby attractions like the Reykjanes Peninsula</li>
                </ul>
                
                <p>The Blue Lagoon is more than a spa --- it's a unique fusion of science, nature, and luxury. Whether you're visiting for wellness, wonder, or a bit of both, it's a rejuvenating highlight of any Icelandic journey.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Back button for blog posts -->
        <div class="container" style="margin-bottom: 50px;">
            <a href="#" class="btn" id="back-to-blog"><i class="fas fa-arrow-left"></i> Back to Blog</a>
        </div>
    </div>
</main>

